\begin_layout Chapter
Classical Field Theory/Terminology that will be seen in QFT
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Intro/Stuff that will be useful in QFT:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Wave physics and many waves equations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Theory of solitons.
 in 1d, solitons are kinks.
 2d are vortices.
 3d are monopoles and 4d instantons.
 Solitons are tightly related to symmetry breaking (e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eq44"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The action
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The action (which is a functional) is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S\left[\phi\right]=\int_{M^{n}}\mathcal{L}\left[\phi\left(x\right)\right]d^{n}x
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 is the lagrangian that describes the system,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mathcal{L} & = & T-V
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

(
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is K.E.
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is P.E.), 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

field
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{n}$
\end_inset

 (Minkowsky space of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

) is the spactime and combines space dimensions (1,2,3) with time dimension
 (and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a coordinate of that spacetime).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The action and the Lagrangian completely characterize the system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
EOMS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How to reformulate functional minimization problems (like action) into PDEs:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\partial_{\phi}S=\partial_{\phi}\mathcal{L}-\partial_{\mu}\left(\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\left(\partial_{\mu}\phi\right)}\right)=0\label{eq:eom1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{\phi}S$
\end_inset

 kind of means 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(x\right)\rightarrow\phi\left(x\right)+\partial\phi\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Examples of actions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Klein-Gordon theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the following action
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S=\int d^{n}x\left(\underbrace{\frac{1}{2}\left(\partial_{\mu}\phi\right)\left(\partial^{\mu}\phi\right)}_{K.E.}-\underbrace{\frac{m}{2}\phi^{2}\left(x\right)}_{P.E.}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is a constant/parameter.
 The EOMs (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:eom1"

\end_inset

) become
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\square+m^{2}\right)\phi\left(x\right)=0,\label{eq:kleinGordonEq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\square=\partial_{t}^{2}-\nabla^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 To obtain the EOMs we differentiated a quadratic function and so we obtained
 a linear PDE (?).The solutions are of the form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi=e^{ikx+i\omega t}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
4th order theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 4th order (in 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

) action :
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S=\int d^{n}x\left(\frac{1}{2}\partial_{\mu}\phi\partial^{\mu}\phi-\underbrace{\frac{\lambda}{4}\left(\phi^{2}-a^{2}\right)^{2}}_{P.E.}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

(this is relevant to describing dynamics of Higgs-Boson).
 The potential is shown in the figure: 
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../ph205KleinGordonPotential.png
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Klein-Gordon potential and equilibrium points
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Eoms (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:eom1"

\end_inset

) becomes that of Solitons with dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\square\phi-\lambda\phi\left(\phi^{2}-a^{2}\right)=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

(this is a cubic equation - called the Klein-Gordon equation - because we
 differentiated a quadratic Lagrangian and assume the K.E.
 part is obtained just like partial differentiating wrt to 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 the K.E.
 term in the Lagrangian).
 If we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla_{x}^{2}\phi-\lambda\phi\left(\phi^{2}-a^{2}\right)=0,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{x}^{2}=d^{2}/dx^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that this is a symmetric equation in 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\rightarrow-\phi$
\end_inset

 but we will see that the soliton breaks the symmetry (it has to (??)).
 This equation turns out to have the solution
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi\left(x\right)=\pm a\tanh\left(\sqrt{\frac{\lambda}{2}}ax\right)\label{eq:eq44}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and notice 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(x=\pm\infty\right)=\pm a$
\end_inset

 and we say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 migrates from one vacuum (which we define to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm a$
\end_inset

) to another vacuum.
 Such behavior defines a soliton.
 Also, the solution if not even like the EOM.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Sine-Gordon theory and Bogomolny Bound
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sine-Gordon theory:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S=\int d^{n}x\left(\frac{1}{2}\partial_{\mu}\phi\partial^{\mu}\phi-\left(1-\cos\phi\right)\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This gives the EOM:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\square\phi+\sin\phi=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{tt}-\phi_{xx}+\sin\phi=0$
\end_inset

.
 This has soliton solutions that interpolate (alternate) between 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=2\pi n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 (these are the minima of the potential).
 The trick of solving such soliton equations is the Bogomolny Bound:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
E & = & T+V\\
 & = & \int_{-\infty}^{\infty}dx\left(\frac{1}{2}\left(\partial_{t}\phi\right)^{2}+\frac{1}{2}\left(\partial_{x}\phi\right)^{2}+\left(1-\cos\phi\right)\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

(where we consider that the K.E.
 is the part that contains derivatives) where each term is positive (adding
 contributions to 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 - trying to find minimum).
 Assume that we have a single kink that moves from 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi m$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi\left(m+1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The potential will look like: 
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../ph205SineGordonPotential.png
	scale 60

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Sine-Gordon equation and assumed behavior of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
E & \geq & \int_{-\infty}^{\infty}dx\left(\frac{1}{2}\phi_{x}^{2}+\left(1-\cos\phi\right)\right)\\
 & = & \int_{-\infty}^{\infty}dx\left[\frac{1}{2}\phi_{x}^{2}+2\sin^{2}\left(\frac{\phi}{2}\right)\right]dx\\
 & = & \int_{-\infty}^{\infty}dx\left(\frac{1}{2}\left[\phi_{x}\pm2\sin\left(\frac{\phi}{2}\right)\right]^{2}\mp2\sin\left(\frac{\phi}{2}\right)\underbrace{\phi_{x}}_{\frac{d\phi}{dx}}\right)dx\\
 & = & \left(\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}dx\frac{1}{2}\left[\phi_{x}\pm2\sin\left(\frac{\phi}{2}\right)\right]^{2}\right)\pm\left.4\cos\left(\frac{\phi}{2}\right)\right|_{-\infty}^{\infty}\\
 & \geq & 8
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.4\cos\left(\frac{\phi}{2}\right)\right|_{-\infty}^{\infty}=8
\end{equation}

\end_inset

because we assumed that the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 moves from one stable equilibrium point: 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi m$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x\rightarrow-\infty$
\end_inset

 to another stable equilibrium point: 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi\left(m+1\right)$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

In order to saturate the bound (i.e.
 to have 
\begin_inset Formula $E=8$
\end_inset

) we have a 1st order equation (BPS equations)*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
this is because 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}dx\frac{1}{2}\left[\phi_{x}\pm2\sin\left(\frac{\phi}{2}\right)\right]^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 is positive so it's contributions can only add to the energy
\end_layout

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi_{x}\pm2\sin\frac{\phi}{2}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 increases then (direction that we move from one vacuum to another) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi_{x}-2\sin\frac{\phi}{2}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We then obtin that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int dx=\int\frac{d\phi}{2\sin\frac{\phi}{2}}=\log\tan\left(\frac{\phi}{4}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and then we invert to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi=4\arctan e^{x-x_{0}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This solution lends itself to interpreting 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 as a particle: it is localized (arctan has an abrupt change - a kink- over
 a narrow window) and has a center of mass given by 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 (this is the center of the region in which the kink is localized).
 With this solution it can be verified that 
\begin_inset Formula $E=8$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Chern-Simons theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S=\frac{k}{4\pi}\int_{M^{3}}Tr\left(AdA+A\wedge A\wedge A\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{3}$
\end_inset

 is a 3d spacetime, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is the gauge 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

field
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and d and 
\begin_inset Formula $\wedge$
\end_inset

 are differential geometry operators.
 EOMs will not be linear because the lagrangian is not quadratic.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial S}{\partial A}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

implies that ('Euler Lagrange equations)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{A}\equiv dA+A\wedge A=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $dA$
\end_inset

 is the magnetic field and 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{A}$
\end_inset

 is the field strength.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Yang-Mills theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S\left[A\right]=Im\tau\int Tr\left(F_{A}\wedge F_{A}+iF_{A}\wedge*F_{A}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $Im\tau>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\theta/2\pi+4\pi i/g^{2}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is called the coupling constant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Path from physics of space-time (special relativity) to quantization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Space-time 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{n}\rightarrow$
\end_inset

Function on 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{n}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fields
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula $\rightarrow$
\end_inset

Action 
\begin_inset Formula $S\left[\phi\right]$
\end_inset

 and Lagrangian 
\begin_inset Formula $L\left[\phi\right]$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\rightarrow$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

Quantization
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Space-timeNotation"

\end_inset

Space-time/Notation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Poincare and Lorentz symmetry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will use space-time coordinates: 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\mu}$
\end_inset

, where greek letters (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu,\nu$
\end_inset

) go from 
\begin_inset Formula $0,...,n-1$
\end_inset

 and label space and time.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
x^{\mu} & = & \left(x^{0},x^{i}\right)\\
 & \equiv & \left(x^{0},\vec{x}\right)\equiv\left(ct,x^{i}\right)
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where roman letters (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j$
\end_inset

) go from 
\begin_inset Formula $1,...,n-1$
\end_inset

 and label space.
 Note that we often set fundamental constants such as 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 to be equal to 1 and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x^{0}=t.\quad\mbox{(units such as \ensuremath{c=1})}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Metric to calculate distance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The metric is 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 and the 
\emph on
distance/interval
\emph default
 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
ds^{2}=g_{\mu\nu}dx^{\mu}dx^{\nu}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $n=4$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are many implications of 
\begin_inset Formula $n=4$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

